==English==
===Etymology===
Japanese [[数独]] (sūdoku), numbers singly

===Noun===
'''sudoku''' (''plural'' '''sudokus''')

====Alternative spellings====
'''su doku'''

====Pronunciation====
*(''[[RP]]''): so͝odō'ko͞o, /sʊˈdəʊku/, /<tt>sU"d@Uku</tt>/<!--NB: no length mark ː/: in IPA & SAMPA as the stress is not on the final syllable-->
*(''US''): so͝odō'ku, /sʊˈdoʊku/, /<tt>sU"doUku</tt>/

#A type of [[puzzle]] in which the solver must fill a grid of ''n'' rows and ''n'' columns (''n'' is typically 9) with the numbers from 1 to ''n'' in such a way that each row, each column and each of several smaller regions into which the grid has been subdivided (in a nine-by-nine puzzle, these regions are usually squares of three rows and three columns) contains each of the numbers once and once only.

====Synonyms====
*[[Number Place]] (''US'')

====Translations====
*Chinese: [[数独]] (shù dú)
*Italian: sudoku ''m''
*Japanese: [[数独]] ([[すどく]])
*Polish: sudoku ''n''

